ly 1870s is covered, followed by the measures Nightingale brought in to improve instruction, including her mentoring relationships with emerging nursing leaders. Nursing historians may be surprised to learn that Nightingale was keeping up on best operating theatre practices in 1898. Struggles with cost-conscious hospital administrators are part of the story, as is the challenge to keep nurses safe at a time when hospitals were dangerous places. ‹/p  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aInfirmièresxBiographiesxGrande-Bretagne. 0aNursesxBiographyxGreat Britain. 0aNurseszGreat BritainvBiography. 0aNursingxEurope. 0aNursingxStudy and teachingxHistoryxGreat Britain. 0aNursingxStudy and teachingzGreat BritainxHistory. 0aNursingzEurope. 0aNursing. 0aSoins infirmiersxEurope. 0aSoins infirmiersxÉtude et enseignementxHistoirexGrande-Bretagne. 0aSoins infirmiers. 4aHistory. 4aMedical: History Of Medicine. 4aSocial Science: Women’s Studies. 7aMEDICAL / History.2bisacsh1 aMcDonald, Lynn, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781554581696423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781554581696/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  aGBV-deGruyter-alles